<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1923-01-03T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1923-01-03T03:00:00-05:00" n="660" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d660">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.74/258: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-01-03T16:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">January 3,
                                        1923—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 6:13
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>3. Your no. 299, December 28, 4 p.m. It is the opinion of Mr. Barnes Moss
                            that he will have the situation well in hand with the new Cabinet and
                            therefore that it would serve no good purpose to send a note of that
                            kind at present. I shall not present the note before it seems necessary
                            unless I am instructed otherwise. Have mailed to Tokyo a copy of this
                            telegram.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>